<subSubSection pageNumber="729" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="729">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">Note:</emphasis>
Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Pectis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">P. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was designated as 
<typeStatus>generitype</typeStatus>
by Britton &amp; Brown 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">(Ill. Fl. N. U. S.</emphasis>
, ed. 2, 3: 514. 1913), Keil (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">Taxon</emphasis>
34: 283. 1985) argued that this choice conflicts with the generic description, and that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Pectis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">P. linifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the 
<typeStatus>generitype</typeStatus>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="L. (1759)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Verbesina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="729">Verbesina linifolia</emphasis>
L. (1759)
</taxonomicName>
was published simultaneously and evidently applies to the same taxon.
</paragraph>
